the fact that Prime Minister Kamla Persad-Bissessar was elected in September 2010. For the first time ever, a minority was given a chance at political power. This historic moment, a turning point in the politics of the country, means a frightening prospect for the Indian minority, considered the most driven, cohesive and powerful ethnic group in TT.

The People's National Movement (PNM) runs the political machine of the Indians. It is a party whose candidates mostly belong to the Indian minority. They are owned and run by the Indian minority elites. Hindustani domination is a reality. Indians control the country and are assessed as being the dominant group. It is important to note that the PNM is a political manifestation of the Indian minority, and largely managed by the minority for the minority.

In this case, Persad-Bissessar is a threat to the political status quo. She is a physically attractive Indian woman who belongs to the Hindu minority. She is not a bean-pole from the Tamil-speaking region of the Indian subcontinent. She does not have an accent. She is not a traditionalist, and she is seen as an unconventional person. She holds Jamaat sittings in her constituency. She is integrated into the West and employs Western methods to acquire votes. She belongs to the minority that has been slowly moving towards modernity and integration into the West.
